  "learnings_before": "- Valproate (syrup, tablet or dispersible) is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies, costs ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg dose, and is the preferred first‑line AED for children ≤ 2 years with focal or generalized seizures unless a contraindication is documented.  \n- Recommended therapeutic range for valproate is 20–30 mg/kg/day; doses outside this window should be adjusted only after confirming a serum valproate level < 50 µg/mL and normal baseline liver enzymes (ALT/AST < 2× ULN) and platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L.  \n- If a prescription section lists a drug and dose, the default action is to continue that regimen unchanged unless the clinical notes explicitly state a dose change, adverse event, or laboratory abnormality.  \n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases when valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable or contraindicated; it is avoided in children with spastic cerebral palsy because sedation occurs in ~30 % of such patients.  \n- Clobazam is not on the Ugandan Essential Medicines List for pediatric epilepsy and is rarely stocked; it should only be used if specifically prescribed by the clinician and serum clobazam levels are available (valproate co‑administration markedly increases clobazam concentrations).  \n- Levetiracetam is an effective non‑aromatic alternative; its cost is 2–3 × that of valproate and dispersible tablets may be intermittently unavailable, so it is considered only when valproate is contraindicated, poorly tolerated, or unavailable in any formulation.  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) should be avoided in any child with a prior drug‑induced rash; if a rash history exists, the regimen defaults to valproate ± levetiracetam.  \n- Adherence ≥ 80 % (based on caregiver report and pharmacy refill data) is required before adding a third agent; otherwise the strategy is to optimise dosing or simplify the existing regimen.  \n- Formulation substitution precedes any change of active drug: when syrup is unaffordable or out of stock, switch to equivalent tablets or dispersible formulation rather than selecting a different AED.  \n- Valproate inhibition of CYP enzymes can raise plasma levels of concurrent antiretrovirals and zidovudine; phenobarbital induction can reduce efficacy of antimalarials and protease‑inhibitor‑based ART, so drug‑interaction checks are mandatory when co‑prescribing.  \n- In infants < 2 years, valproate carries a higher risk of hepatotoxicity and hyperammonemia; baseline and repeat LFTs and ammonia should be obtained before initiation and after any dose increase.  \n- Cost‑effectiveness hierarchy for adjuncts: phenobarbital (cheapest, widely available) is preferred over levetiracetam when an adjunct is required and no sedation or interaction contraindications exist.  \n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window and no safety concerns are present, the recommended next step is to maintain the current valproate dose unchanged.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Both valproate and carbamazepine are guideline‑consistent first‑line options for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; selection is guided by drug availability, tolerability, and the need for laboratory monitoring.\n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are acceptable for focal epilepsy but must be avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or hypersensitivity.\n- Before any change of therapy, clinicians must obtain baseline safety labs (ALT/AST < 2 × ULN, platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within normal limits) and, when feasible, a serum level of the current AED.\n- Dose optimisation is performed first: if the current dose is < 20 mg/kg/day for valproate or < 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine and seizure control is suboptimal, the dose should be titrated upward in 25‑50 mg increments every 1–2 weeks before considering drug substitution or adjuncts.\n- Exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone in children with cerebral palsy are not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; they require confirmation (e.g., seizure diary or video‑EEG) before altering the regimen.\n- The decision hierarchy is: (1) confirm seizure‑free status (≥ 6 months) and adherence ≥ 80 %; (2) verify normal safety labs; (3) maintain the current regimen unchanged; (4) if either seizure control or labs are inadequate, proceed to dose optimisation; (5) if optimisation fails, consider switching to valproate (after normal LFTs) or adding levetiracetam as an adjunct.\n- Valproate is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies at ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; carbamazepine is similarly stocked at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; levetiracetam is 2–3 × more expensive and often unavailable, so it is reserved for documented valproate intolerance or failure.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable; it may be used in spastic cerebral palsy only with close monitoring for sedation, otherwise it is avoided.\n- Initiation of valproate requires baseline liver function tests and ammonia; if ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or ammonia is elevated, valproate should be deferred and an alternative AED chosen.\n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window (20–30 mg/kg/day) and safety labs are normal, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current dose without escalation or adjunct addition.",
